      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Find the indicated derivative. In each case, state the version of the Chain Rule that you are using.
            <ol marker="a.">
              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>\frac{df}{dt}</m>, if <m>f(x,y) = 2x^2y</m>, <m>x=\cos(t)</m>, and <m>y=\ln(t)</m>.
                </p>
              </li>

              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>\frac{\partial f}{\partial w}</m>, if <m>f(x,y) = 2x^2y</m>, <m>x=w+z^2</m>, and <m>y=\frac{2z+1}{w}</m>
                </p>
              </li>

              <li>
                <p>
                  <m>\frac{\partial f}{\partial v}</m>, if <m>f(x,y,z) = 2x^2y+z^3</m>, <m>x=u-v+2w</m>, <m>y=w2^v-u^3</m>, and <m>z = u^2-v</m>
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>

        <answer>
          <ol marker="a.">
            <li>
              <p>
                The chain rule says that
                <md>
                  <mrow>\frac{df}{dt} \amp = \frac{\partial f}{\partial x}\frac{dx}{dt} + \frac{\partial f}{\partial y}\frac{dy}{dt}</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp = (4xy)\left(-\sin(t)\right) + (2x^2)\left(\frac{1}{t}\right)</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp = -4 \cos(t) \sin(t) \ln(t) + \frac{2\cos^2(t)}{t}</mrow>
                </md>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                By the chain rule we have
                <md>
                  <mrow>\frac{\partial f}{\partial w} \amp = \frac{\partial f}{\partial x} \frac{\partial x}{\partial w}+ \frac{\partial f}{\partial y} \frac{\partial y}{\partial w}</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp = \left( 4xy \right)\left( 1 \right) + \left( 2x^2 \right)\left( -\frac{2z+1}{w^2} \right)</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp = \left( \frac{(2z+1)4(w+z^2)y}{w} \right) - \left( \frac{2(2z+1)((w+z^2)^2}{w^2} \right)</mrow>
                </md>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                By the chain rule we have
                <md>
                  <mrow>\frac{\partial f}{\partial v} \amp = \frac{\partial f}{\partial x} \frac{\partial x}{\partial v}+ \frac{\partial f}{\partial y} \frac{\partial y}{\partial v} + \frac{\partial f}{\partial z} \frac{\partial z}{\partial v}</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp = \left( 4xy \right)\left( -1 \right) + \left( 2x^2 \right)\left( w 2^v \ln(2) \right) + \left( 3z^2 \right)\left( -1 \right)</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp = -4(u-v+2w)(w2^v-u^3) + 2(u-v+2w)^2w 2^v\ln(2) - 3(u-v+2w)^2</mrow>
                </md>.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </answer>

        <solution>
          <ol marker="a.">
            <li>
              <p>
                The chain rule says that
                <md>
                  <mrow>\frac{df}{dt} \amp = \frac{\partial f}{\partial x}\frac{dx}{dt} + \frac{\partial f}{\partial y}\frac{dy}{dt}</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp = (4xy)\left(-\sin(t)\right) + (2x^2)\left(\frac{1}{t}\right)</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp = -4 \cos(t) \sin(t) \ln(t) + \frac{2\cos^2(t)}{t}</mrow>
                </md>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                By the chain rule we have
                <md>
                  <mrow>\frac{\partial f}{\partial w} \amp = \frac{\partial f}{\partial x} \frac{\partial x}{\partial w}+ \frac{\partial f}{\partial y} \frac{\partial y}{\partial w}</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp = \left( 4xy \right)\left( 1 \right) + \left( 2x^2 \right)\left( -\frac{2z+1}{w^2} \right)</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp = \left( \frac{(2z+1)4(w+z^2)y}{w} \right) - \left( \frac{2(2z+1)((w+z^2)^2}{w^2} \right)</mrow>
                </md>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                By the chain rule we have
                <md>
                  <mrow>\frac{\partial f}{\partial v} \amp = \frac{\partial f}{\partial x} \frac{\partial x}{\partial v}+ \frac{\partial f}{\partial y} \frac{\partial y}{\partial v} + \frac{\partial f}{\partial z} \frac{\partial z}{\partial v}</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp = \left( 4xy \right)\left( -1 \right) + \left( 2x^2 \right)\left( w 2^v \ln(2) \right) + \left( 3z^2 \right)\left( -1 \right)</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp = -4(u-v+2w)(w2^v-u^3) + 2(u-v+2w)^2w 2^v\ln(2) - 3(u-v+2w)^2</mrow>
                </md>.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </solution>
        
      </exercise>


      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Let <m>z = u^2 - v^2</m> and suppose that
            <md>
              <mrow>u \amp  = e^x\cos(y)</mrow>
              <mrow>v \amp  = e^x\sin(y)</mrow>
            </md>
            <ol marker="a.">
              <li>
                <p>
                  Find the values of <m>u</m> and <m>v</m> that correspond to <m>x=0</m> and <m>y=2\pi/3</m>.
                </p>
              </li>

              <li>
                <p>
                  Use the Chain Rule to find the general partial derivatives
                  <me>
                    \frac{\partial z}{\partial x}
                            \ 
                            \mbox{and} 
                            \ 
                            \frac{\partial z}{\partial y}
                  </me>
                  and then determine both <m>\frac{\partial z}{\partial x}\bigm|_{(0, \frac{2\pi}{3})}</m> and <m>\frac{\partial z}{\partial y}\bigm|_{(0, \frac{2\pi}{3})}</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>

        <answer>
          <ol marker="a.">
            <li>
              <p>
                Evaluating <m>u</m> and <m>v</m> at <m>x=0</m> and <m>y=2\pi/3</m> yields
                <me>
                  u(0,2\pi/3) = \cos(2\pi/3) = -\frac{1}{2} \ \text{ and }  \ v(0,2\pi/3) = \sin(2\pi/3) = \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}
                </me>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                By the Chain Rule we have
                <md>
                  <mrow>\frac{\partial z}{\partial x} \amp = \frac{\partial z}{\partial u} \frac{\partial u}{\partial x} + \frac{\partial z}{\partial v} \frac{\partial v}{\partial x}</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp = 2ue^x\cos(y) -2ve^x \sin(y)</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp = 2e^{2x}\cos^2(y) - 2e^{2x}\sin^2(y)</mrow>
                </md>
                and
                <md>
                  <mrow>\frac{\partial z}{\partial y} \amp = \frac{\partial z}{\partial u} \frac{\partial u}{\partial y} + \frac{\partial z}{\partial v} \frac{\partial v}{\partial y}</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp = -2ue^x\sin(y) -2ve^x \cos(y)</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp = -2e^{2x}\cos(y)\sin(y) - 2e^{2x}\sin(y)\cos(y)</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp = -4e^{2x}\cos(y) \sin(y)</mrow>
                </md>.
                Note that
                <me>
                  \frac{\partial z}{\partial x} = 2u^2-2v^2 \ \text{ and }  \ \frac{\partial z}{\partial y} = -4uv
                </me>,
                so
                <md>
                  <mrow>\frac{\partial z}{\partial x}\bigm|_{(0, \frac{2\pi}{3})} \amp = 2\left(-\frac{1}{2}\right)^2 -2\left(\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}\right)^2 = -1</mrow>
                  <mrow>\frac{\partial z}{\partial y}\bigm|_{(0, \frac{2\pi}{3})} \amp = -4\left(-\frac{1}{2}\right)\left(\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}\right) = \frac{2\sqrt{3}}{2}</mrow>
                </md>.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </answer>

        <solution>
          <ol marker="a.">
            <li>
              <p>
                Evaluating <m>u</m> and <m>v</m> at <m>x=0</m> and <m>y=2\pi/3</m> yields
                <me>
                  u(0,2\pi/3) = \cos(2\pi/3) = -\frac{1}{2} \ \text{ and }  \ v(0,2\pi/3) = \sin(2\pi/3) = \frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}
                </me>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                By the Chain Rule we have
                <md>
                  <mrow>\frac{\partial z}{\partial x} \amp = \frac{\partial z}{\partial u} \frac{\partial u}{\partial x} + \frac{\partial z}{\partial v} \frac{\partial v}{\partial x}</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp = 2ue^x\cos(y) -2ve^x \sin(y)</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp = 2e^{2x}\cos^2(y) - 2e^{2x}\sin^2(y)</mrow>
                </md>
                and
                <md>
                  <mrow>\frac{\partial z}{\partial y} \amp = \frac{\partial z}{\partial u} \frac{\partial u}{\partial y} + \frac{\partial z}{\partial v} \frac{\partial v}{\partial y}</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp = -2ue^x\sin(y) -2ve^x \cos(y)</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp = -2e^{2x}\cos(y)\sin(y) - 2e^{2x}\sin(y)\cos(y)</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp = -4e^{2x}\cos(y) \sin(y)</mrow>
                </md>.
                Note that
                <me>
                  \frac{\partial z}{\partial x} = 2u^2-2v^2 \ \text{ and }  \ \frac{\partial z}{\partial y} = -4uv
                </me>,
                so
                <md>
                  <mrow>\frac{\partial z}{\partial x}\bigm|_{(0, \frac{2\pi}{3})} \amp = 2\left(-\frac{1}{2}\right)^2 -2\left(\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}\right)^2 = -1</mrow>
                  <mrow>\frac{\partial z}{\partial y}\bigm|_{(0, \frac{2\pi}{3})} \amp = -4\left(-\frac{1}{2}\right)\left(\frac{\sqrt{3}}{2}\right) = \frac{2\sqrt{3}}{2}</mrow>
                </md>.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </solution>

      </exercise>


