      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Suppose that the temperature on a metal plate is given by
            the function <m>T</m> with
            <me>
              T(x,y) = 100-(x^2 + 4y^2),
            </me>
            where the temperature is measured in degrees Fahrenheit
            and <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> are each measured in feet.
            Now suppose that an ant is walking on the metal plate in such a way that it walks in a straight line from the point <m>(1,4)</m> to the point <m>(5,6)</m>.
            <ol marker="a.">
              <li>
                <p>
                  Find parametric equations <m>(x(t),y(t))</m> for the ant's coordinates as it walks the line from <m>(1,4)</m> to <m>(5,6)</m>.
                </p>
              </li>

              <li>
                <p>
                  What can you say about <m>\frac{dx}{dt}</m> and <m>\frac{dy}{dt}</m> for every value of <m>t</m>?
                </p>
              </li>

              <li>
                <p>
                  Determine the instantaneous rate of change in temperature with respect to <m>t</m> that the ant is experiencing at the moment it is halfway from <m>(1,4)</m> to <m>(5,6)</m>, using your parametric equations for <m>x</m> and <m>y</m>.  Include units on your answer.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>

        <answer>
          <ol marker="a.">
            <li>
              <p>
                <me>
                  x(t) = 1 + 4t \ \text{ and }  \ y(t) = 4 + 2t
                </me>
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                We have <m>\frac{dx}{dt} = 4</m> and <m>\frac{dy}{dt} = 2</m> both constant.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <me>
                  \frac{dT}{dt}\biggm|_{t=1/2} = -8(3) - 16(5) = 104 \ \frac{^{\circ}\text{F} }{\text{ ft } }
                </me>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </answer>

        <solution>
          <ol marker="a.">
            <li>
              <p>
                A direction vector for this line is <m>\langle 5-1, 6-4 \rangle = \langle 4, 2 \rangle</m>,
                so parametric equations <m>(x(t),y(t))</m> for the ant's coordinates as it walks the line from <m>(1,4)</m> to <m>(5,6)</m> are
                <me>
                  x(t) = 1 + 4t \ \text{ and }  \ y(t) = 4 + 2t
                </me>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Since <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> are linear functions of <m>t</m>,
                we see that <m>\frac{dx}{dt} = 4</m> and <m>\frac{dy}{dt} = 2</m> are both constant.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                We want <m>\frac{dT}{dt}\bigm|_{t=1/2}</m>.
                The Chain Rule tells us that
                <md>
                  <mrow>\frac{dT}{dt} \amp = \frac{\partial T}{\partial x} \frac{dx}{dt} + \frac{\partial T}{\partial y} \frac{dy}{dt}</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp = (-2x)(4) + (-8y)(2)</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp = -8(1 + 4t) - 16(4 + 2t)</mrow>
                </md>.
                So
                <me>
                  \frac{dT}{dt}\biggm|_{t=1/2} = -8(3) - 16(5) = 104 \ \frac{^{\circ}\text{F} }{\text{ ft } }
                </me>.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </solution>

        
      </exercise>


      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            There are several proposed formulas to approximate the surface
            area of the human body.
            One model<fn>DuBois D, DuBois DF. A formula to
                 estimate the approximate surface area if height and weight be
                 known.  <em>Arch Int Med</em> 1916;17:863-71.</fn> uses the formula
            <me>
              A(h,w) = 0.0072 h^{0.725}w^{0.425},
            </me>
            where <m>A</m> is the surface area in square meters, <m>h</m> is the
            height in centimeters, and <m>w</m> is the weight in kilograms.
          </p>

          <p>
            Since a person's height <m>h</m> and weight <m>w</m> change over time,
            <m>h</m> and <m>w</m> are functions of time
            <m>t</m>. Let us think about what is happening to a child whose height
            is <m>60</m> centimeters and weight is <m>9</m> kilograms. Suppose,
            furthermore, that
            <m>h</m> is increasing at an instantaneous rate of 20 centimeters per year and <m>w</m> is
            increasing at an instantaneous rate of <m>5</m> kg per year.
          </p>

          <p>
            Determine the instantaneous rate at which the child's surface area is changing at this point in time.
          </p>
        </statement>

        <answer>
          <p>
            <me>
              \frac{dA}{dt}\biggm|_{(60,9)} \approx 0.1703 \ \frac{\text{m} ^2}{\text{ yr } }
            </me>
          </p>
        </answer>

        <solution>
          <p>
            We want to find <m>\frac{dA}{dt}\bigm|_{(60,9)}</m> given that
            <m>\frac{dh}{dt} = 20</m> and <m>\frac{dw}{dt} = 5</m>.
            The Chain Rule tells us that
            <md>
              <mrow>\frac{dA}{dt} \amp = \frac{\partial A}{\partial h} \frac{dh}{dt} + \frac{\partial A}{\partial w} \frac{dw}{dt}</mrow>
              <mrow>\amp = 0.00522h^{-0.275}w^{0.425}(20) + 0.00306h^{0.725}w^{-0.575}(5)</mrow>
            </md>.
          </p>
          <p>
            So
            <me>
              \frac{dA}{dt}\biggm|_{(60,9)} \approx 0.1703 \ \frac{\text{m} ^2}{\text{ yr } }
            </me>.
          </p>
        </solution>
       
      </exercise>


      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            Let <m>z = f(x,y) = 50 - (x+1)^2 - (y+3)^2</m> and <m>z = h(x,y) = 24 - 2x - 6y</m>.
          </p>

          <p>
            Suppose a person is walking on the surface <m>z = f(x,y)</m> in such a way that she walks the curve which is the intersection of <m>f</m> and <m>h</m>.
            <ol marker="a.">
              <li>
                <p>
                  Show that <m>x(t) = 4 \cos(t)</m> and <m>y(t) = 4 \sin(t)</m> is a parameterization of the <q>shadow</q> in the <m>xy</m>-plane of the curve that is the intersection of the graphs of <m>f</m> and <m>h</m>.
                </p>
              </li>

              <li>
                <p>
                  Use the parameterization from part (a) to find the instantaneous rate at which her height is changing with respect to time at the instant <m>t = 2\pi/3</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </p>
        </statement>

        <answer>
          <ol marker="a.">
            <li>
              <p>
                Notice that <m>f(x,y) = h(x,y)</m> when
                <m>50-x^2-2x-1-y^2-6y-9=24-2x-6y</m> or when <m>x^2+y^2=16</m>.
                This is the circle centered at the origin of radius 4, which has a parameterization
                <m>x(t) = 4 \cos(t)</m> and <m>y(t) = 4 \sin(t)</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <me>
                  \frac{df}{dt}\biggm|_{t=2\pi/3} \approx 243.78
                </me>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </answer>

        <solution>
          <ol marker="a.">
            <li>
              <p>
                Notice that <m>f(x,y) = h(x,y)</m> when
                <m>50-x^2-2x-1-y^2-6y-9=24-2x-6y</m> or when <m>x^2+y^2=16</m>.
                This is the circle centered at the origin of radius 4, which has a parameterization
                <m>x(t) = 4 \cos(t)</m> and <m>y(t) = 4 \sin(t)</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                We want to find <m>\frac{df}{dt}\bigm|_{t=2\pi/3}</m>.
                The Chain Rule tells us that
                <md>
                  <mrow>\frac{df}{dt} \amp = \frac{\partial f}{\partial x} \frac{dx}{dt} + \frac{\partial f}{\partial y} \frac{dy}{dt}</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp = (-2(x+1))(-4\sin(t)) + (-3(y+3)^2)(4\cos(t))</mrow>
                </md>.
                Now <m>x(2\pi/3) = -2</m> and <m>y(2\pi/3) = 2\sqrt{3}</m>, so
                <me>
                  \frac{df}{dt}\biggm|_{t=2\pi/3} \approx 243.78
                </me>.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </solution>

        
      </exercise>



      <exercise>
        <statement>
          <p>
            The voltage <m>V</m> (in volts) across a circuit is given by Ohm's Law: <m>V = IR</m>, where <m>I</m> is the current (in amps) in the circuit and <m>R</m> is the resistance (in ohms). Suppose we connect two resistors with resistances <m>R_1</m> and <m>R_2</m> in parallel as shown in <xref ref="F_10_5_CR_Circuit">Figure</xref>. The total resistance <m>R</m> in the circuit is then given by
            <me>
              \frac{1}{R} = \frac{1}{R_1} + \frac{1}{R_2}.
            </me>
          </p>

          
            <sidebyside>
              <ol marker="a.">
                <li>
                  <p>
                    Assume that the current, <m>I</m>, and the resistances, <m>R_1</m> and <m>R_2</m>, are changing over time, <m>t</m>. Use the Chain Rule to write a formula for <m>\frac{dV}{dt}</m>.
                  </p>
                </li>

                <li>
                  <p>
                    Suppose that, at some particular point in time, we measure the current to be 3 amps and that the current is increasing at <m>\frac{1}{10}</m> amps per second, while resistance <m>R_1</m> is 2 ohms and decreasing at the rate of 0.2 ohms per second and <m>R_2</m> is 1 ohm and increasing at the rate of <m>0.5</m> ohms per second. At what rate is the voltage changing at this point in time?
                  </p>
                </li>
              </ol>
              <figure xml:id="F_10_5_CR_Circuit">
            <caption>Resistors in parallel.</caption>
              <image width="73%" source="images/fig_10_5_resistors"/>
              </figure>
            </sidebyside>
        </statement>

        <answer>
          <ol marker="a.">
            <li>
              <p>
                <me>
                  \frac{dV}{dt} =  \left(\frac{R_1R_2}{R_1+R_2}\right)\frac{dI}{dt} + \left(\frac{IR_2^2}{(R_1+R_2)^2}\right) \frac{dR_1}{dt} +  \left(\frac{IR_1^2}{(R_1+R_2)^2}\right) \frac{dR_2}{dt}
                </me>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                <me>
                  \frac{2}{3} \ \frac{\text{V} }{\text{ sec } }
                </me>
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </answer>

        <solution>
          <ol marker="a.">
            <li>
              <p>
                Given that <m>R = \frac{R_1R_2}{R_1+R_2}</m> we have
                <me>
                  V(I,R_1,R_2) = \frac{IR_1R_2}{R_1+R_2}
                </me>.
                The Chain Rule tells us that
                <md>
                  <mrow>\frac{dV}{dt} \amp = \frac{\partial V}{\partial I} \frac{dI}{dt} + \frac{\partial V}{\partial R_1} \frac{dR_1}{dt} + \frac{\partial V}{\partial R_2} \frac{dR_2}{dt}</mrow>
                  <mrow>\amp =  \left(\frac{R_1R_2}{R_1+R_2}\right)\frac{dI}{dt} + \left(\frac{IR_2^2}{(R_1+R_2)^2}\right) \frac{dR_1}{dt} +  \left(\frac{IR_1^2}{(R_1+R_2)^2}\right) \frac{dR_2}{dt}</mrow>
                </md>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Let <m>t_0</m> be this time, then
                <me>
                  \frac{dV}{dt}\biggm|_{t=t_0} = \left(\frac{2}{3}\right)(0.1) + \left(\frac{1}{3}\right)(-0.2) + \left(\frac{4}{3}\right)(0.5) = \frac{2}{3} \ \frac{\text{V} }{\text{ sec } }
                </me>.

                <me>\int_0^3 \frac{y^2}{2}\left.\right|_{y=0}^{y=x}\, dx = \int_0^3 \frac{x^2}{2}\, dx = \left. \frac{x^3}{6} \right|_{x=0}^{x=3} = \left. \frac{x^3}{6}\middle|_0^3 \right. = \frac{x^3}{6}_{\|_0^3} = \frac{x^3}{6}_{\vert_0^3}= \frac{x^3}{6}_{\rvert_0^3} = \frac{27}{6}</me>


              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </solution>

